title: Cyclone Alfred forms in Gulf of Carpentaria
text:
Cyclone Alfred forms in Gulf of Carpentaria, BOM warns of damaging winds, rain Updated February 20, 2017 09:57:33 Map: Borroloola 0854 
A category one cyclone has formed in the Gulf of Carpentaria but is due to weaken before heading towards the Northern Territory coast. 
The slow-moving low had been threatening to turn into a cyclone for days, and finally intensified into Cyclone Alfred about 7:00am. 
The Bureau of Meteorology said the system was currently over water, north of Borroloola in the Northern Territory. 
It is forecast to weaken in the southern Gulf waters prior to making landfall later today. 
Gusts up to 95 kilometres per hour have been recorded and some Gulf communities have received half a metre of rain since Friday. 
More heavy rain is forecast for the Gulf, with the possibility of 150 millimetres in 24 hours and localised flash flooding. 
The rain will possibly extend south to Burketown and Doomadgee in Queensland on Tuesday.
